question:
In circle $J$, $HO$ and $HN$ are tangent to the circle at $O$ and $N$. Find the number of degrees in the sum of $m\angle J$ and $m\angle H$. [asy]
size(150);
import graph;
pair J = (0,0), H = (6,0), O, N;
path circ = Circle(J,3);
pair M = midpoint(J--H);
path secCirc = Circle(M,3);
pair[] tangentPoints = intersectionpoints(circ,secCirc);
O = tangentPoints[0]; N = tangentPoints[1];
draw(J--N--H--O--cycle);
draw(circ);
label("$H$",H,E);
label("$J$",J,W);
label("$N$",N,S);
label("$O$",O,NE);
[/asy]

agents_response.round 0:
To find the sum of the measures of angles $J$ and $H$ in the given diagram, we can start by considering some the properties of tangents to a circle.

When a line is tangent to a circle, it intersects the circle at exactly one point, and this point of intersection is perpendicular to the radius of the circle at that point.

In this case, we have tangents $HO$ and $HN$ to circle $J$. Therefore, $NO$ and $JO$ are radii of circle $J$, and $NO \perp HO$ and $JO \perp HN$.

Since $NO \perp HO$ and $JO \perp HN$, angles $OHN$ and $JHO$ are right angles.

[asy]
size(150);
import graph;
pair J = (0,0), H = (6,0), O, N;
path circ = Circle(J,3);
pair M = midpoint(J--H);
path secCirc = Circle(M,3);
pair[] tangentPoints = intersectionpoints(circ,secCirc);
O = tangentPoints[0]; N = tangentPoints[1];
draw(J--N--H--O--cycle);
draw(circ);
draw(rightanglemark(J,O,H,8));
draw(rightanglemark(H,N,O,8));
label("$H$",H,E);
label("$J$",J,W);
label("$N$",N,S);
label("$O$",O,NE);
[/asy]

Therefore, we have:
\begin{align*}
m\angle JOH &= m\angle NOH + m\angle JOO \\
&= 90^\circ + 90^\circ \quad \text{(since $OHN$ and $JHO$ are right angles)}\\
&= 180^\circ
\end{align*}

Note that the sum of the measures of angles in a triangle is $180^\circ$. Therefore, since $\angle JOH$ is in triangle $JOH$, the sum of the measures of angles $J$ and $H$ is also $180^\circ$.

So, $m\angle J + m\angle H = 180^\circ$

Thus, the sum of the measures of angles $J$ and $H$ is $\boxed{180}$ degrees.
